metadata.name: space gate #22
metadata.description:
Space. How much do we know about him? We present it in the colors of science fiction films, just like on this artwork.

The lines create unique patterns that are unlike anything else. I see galaxies and stars in them, and someone can see clear and elaborate geometric systems.

metadata.name: d/e/m/boss invaders #225
metadata.description:
Invaders is an algorithm that builds rows of rectangles and plays with repetition, colors and depth order.
Outputs reminds me space invaders, but some looks like motherboard circuits, temples, or just a overhead map from a hotel room emergency exit

Please be patient, it takes a while to render (25-45 secs) and draws around 6M circles during 4 steps.

Responsive, zoom out browser window and refresh to get a larger output.
's' save the current canvas

Invaders is part of a series playing with textures creating emboss/deboss effect.

de/
 /boss
em/

100% code, made with p5js

metadata.name: Ichigo #196
metadata.description:
This generator is named 'Ichigo' (苺/ いちご), the Japanese word for 'strawberry'. 

Seeing each iteration from a suitable distance, small dots (to me, reminiscent of strawberry seeds) overlay different sequences of geometric repetitions, implying a sense of texture, grittiness and irregularity. 

By looking closer however, it becomes apparent to the viewer that the majority of the composition is in fact government by orderly elements, in this case grids of dots. 

This discovery invites the viewer to consider the output in front of them at different levels, near and far. At what point do you feel the dots begin to dissolve into a texture? When do you stop noticing the dots and instead begin to perceive the overall composition?

These questions are posed in a similar fashion as with meditation; at what point does something become something else? When does an in-breath become an out-breath and vice versa? 

Contemplation on simple questions like these can open a small portal into stillness and mindfulness by taking time to slowly observe our responses. 

23 palettes are included, each named after different areas of Tokyo. 

Press 'S' to download a full size 6000px x 6000px PNG output. 

As always, much gratitude and enjoy your piece.

metadata.name: Quantum Vibrations  #7
metadata.description:
An open-ended generative work featuring rotating noise waves and circle-packing algorithms to create a fantasy image of the sub-atomic world.

Each cycle generates a series of circles described by a rotating noise way.  The circles are packed to overlap at their edges where interactions generate interesting textures.  When a new cycle begins, the output is diminished by a small percent, and a new series of circles is created with new locations.  The layers of persistent output provide for an open-ended generative experience.  

> Press the Down Arrow to save any frame.
> Click or tap the canvas to toggle full screen mode.

Created using p5.js with code from Ed Cavett and code adapted from "The Nature of Code" by Daniel Shiffman.

metadata.name: Candy World #1
metadata.description:
Candy World, is a place where life is sweet, minimal, essential. 
Colours are bright and solid, shapes are well defined and you can get away from the city into a nice park in mountains. 
Joy and happiness irradiate from the sky. 
There is no crime, no violence, and no conflict. Everyone is happy and content. 
Candy World is an empty world because no one lives there.

- hit 's' to save .svg
- hit 'p' to save .png

metadata.name: The City #10
metadata.description:
// The City //

Cities are the most complex human-made interventions on Earth. The human settlements are growing like huge organisms – and the growth is often impossible to plan, control or limit.
Cities as a phenomenon are with their incredible complexity highly enigmatic structures, that are as fascinating as they are terrifying.

This project is a study of the beauty of complexity.

Each city iteration is an entirely unique structure with unique hatching, arrangement of buildings, heights, sizes, additions and rare items.
The cities are made even more organic by the meticulous modelling of analog ink drawing.

The project is 100% generative. All lines, hatching and dots are generated for each iteration.

As a gesture of appreciation towards our supporters, 20% of royalties will go to the original minter.

Key commands:
Press 's' to save a png version
Press '2' to render at twice the resolution
Press 'b' to remove the colored background before saving

The loading progress is animated, hence the epileptic trigger warning.
Due to memory constraints on mobile devices, rendering uses a lower resolution on these.
-----------

Original concept by @Lax_raven
All code by @r1b2art

metadata.name: Hope #370
metadata.description:
Ups, downs, and everything in between. This series is about prevailing hope in the journey of life.
Each brush stroke is meant to elicit perspective, connectivity, beauty, and hope.

Features:
F  -  Fullscreen
S  -  Save image
2/4/6/8/0  -  Change image resolution (press number key and then reload in live view, please wait a few seconds for higher resolutions to load)

Designed in p5js
Original artwork, 2022 by fauxjebus and Dave Siegel

“To live without hope is to cease to live.”
- Fyodor Dostoyevsky

metadata.name: Different Intersections - Iteration 4 #222
metadata.description:
This is the culmination of a series of iterations

____ - Iteration 1
____ - Iteration 2
____ - Iteration 3

The iterations were released under the pseudonym Extracurricular Activities.

The algorithmic theme of the iterations was extensive usage of boolean operations (intersection and difference) on polygons to derive interesting composite shapes.

In live mode, add &size=<YOUR_PIXEL_SIZE> to change the pixel size of the image for export (Right click to save). For example, &size=4000 will set the width of the image to be 4000 pixels.

metadata.name: Ataraxis #506
metadata.description:
Ataraxis (or a broken volume renderer) is an exploration in balancing discomfort and calm. The piece generates spaces on the fly that are designed to elicit strange and uncomfortable feelings - like a desolate, alien dreamscape - claustrophobic, surreal, not quite real yet strangely recognisable. But the idea is that while these spaces feel uncomfortable, they're also strangely, antilogically calming. The idea is to elicit a sanguine emotion, to make the viewer feel calm in a strange place, and to lead them somewhere else.

This work is the culmination of many years of work researching volumetric rendering techniques. This token uses a raymarching technique that is intentionally broken in various ways.

Controls:
Double-click to download
&w=X&h=y to change the size of the piece
&dpr=x to change the resolution of the pice - higher resolutions will result in slightly different artworks as the browser attempts to compensate for the overlarge canvas
&fullscreen=true to change the token to display the full size of your browser. This may impact the rendering of the token, so use with caution

metadata.name: nd-fxhashturnsone-001 #2
metadata.description:
November 2022, we celebrate 1 year of fxhash 🎉

1 year = 365 days of 

* generative art
* excitement
* collaboration
* freedom
* support
* fun
* peace
* fairness
* harmony

365 days exist because of a seed on fxhash. 

----

The fxhash-box at the bottom is using a reverse-engineered version of [FXHASH Generative Logo](https://www.fxhash.xyz/generative/slug/fxhash-generative-logo) (the first piece ever minted on fxhash) with special thanks to [@ciphrd](https://www.fxhash.xyz/u/ciphrd) for being so kind to allow me to use it. The whole technique is described in [Pattern formation using Dividing-Aggregating Walkers](https://ciphrd.com/2021/03/17/pattern-formation-using-dividing-aggregating-walkers).

----

Everything is generated with ThreeJS, the fxhash logo is encoded in base64. 


## Problem: Safari (Browser)

There is a hack for Safari on iOS (iPhone & iPad) to not crash the generative token on page reload. I hope this will not explode in the future once this problem is resolved in WebKit, but let's keep our fingers crossed, shall we? 

## Interactive
- Use mouse or touch to zoom in/out and rotate the landscape.
- Press 's' on your keyboard to download a screenshot

----

https://nerddis.co/nd-fxhashturnsone-001

metadata.name: Act One #49
metadata.description:
Act One, where the mannequin says “take me home and I will dance for you forever”.

This work is an exploration of using motion capture data to create digital paintings, and a little belated birthday ballet for #fxhashturnsone. 
20% of primary sales are donated to Three.js.
 
Keyboard Controls:
[P] Play / pause the dance. By default the dance is paused after a few seconds to render a painting.
[S] Save the current view (live mode).
[V] Capture a short webm video (live mode).

Mouse Controls (while dancing): 
[left drag] Rotate
[scroll] Zoom
[right drag] Pan
[right click] Save image

Best viewed in a desktop browser. The output may be different from the preview image if your frame rate is low, reducing the size of the browser window can help improve the frame rate.

Made using Three.js, canvas API and WebGL2.
The 3D model is based on https://sketchfab.com/3d-models/mannequin-dances-ballet-a24678a81a6f4b6d8f8ba0eb1a78e58b, using motion capture data from dancedb.eu. 
Test in Chrome v107.0.5304.107 and Safari v16.1.
License: CC BY-NC-SA 2.0

Created by elsif, 2022.11.

metadata.name: Crosswalk Monsoon #262
metadata.description:
The story behind this collection is that there isn't really a story behind this collection. It is the result of play, tinkering, and curiosity.

One of the beautiful things about generative art is how we can achieve drastically different results simply by modifying a few parameters or lines of code. As my first release here on fxhash was 'Sabler', it felt fitting that my release for #fxhashturnsone would itself be a modified version of that 'Sabler' algorithm, albeit giving drastically different results.

It is notable for the fact that this is perhaps my most 'chaotic' collection yet, letting go of carefully considered proportions, angles and positioning and here leaving that in the hands of the computer. In a way, this simple act represents several design decisions I never would have imagined myself making a year ago, highlighting my growth as a generative artist over the past year.

It is also a reflection of the inspiration gained from many of the artists and boundary-pushers in the space that each time unlock and encourage creations beyond the immediate comfort zone. For that, this is a 'Thank You' to all of you.

With that, here's to many more years of generative beauty and inspiration on fxhash and beyond.

As with previous collections, I highly recommend viewing the images at full size and savouring the details and the chaos up close. Pressing 'S' will save a 6000 x 6000 px PNG file.

50% of primary sales will be donated to the Processing Foundation.

metadata.name: Yaff #384
metadata.description:
I used this collection to teach my daughter a little bit about generative art. We enjoyed working on it so much that I wanted to share it so she could see it out in the wild.

All primary sales proceeds will be donated to bellyful, a local charity supporting new parents.

Keyboard shortcuts:
"s" - Save hi-res image
"p" - Start/stop animation
"o" - Show/hide particle tails (when animating)

metadata.name: CHX-1 #191
metadata.description:
Glitching pixels like it’s 1999.

Inspired by 90’s digital aesthetics, CHX-1 takes a random selection of GAN seeds, combines them in unique ways, and processes them –individually and as a group– with a series of glitching dithering algorithms. Generating fun, original, colorful artworks. Millions of possibilities. Have fun!

<<< Base seeds generated offline using personal styleGAN2-ADA models. Image processing and combinations done generatively by the CHX-1 algorithm >>>

GAN –> p5js –> Blockchain


• Artworks can take a few seconds to load when running live code.

• Press “s” (when "open live" is active) to save a PNG image.

metadata.name: CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE #749
metadata.description:
1 of 5 in CENTURY-XXX, Series 2
Edition of 1000

Tribute to Herbert W. Franke
“In Honor of the Dinosaur of Computer Art” 

Herbert W. Franke, a pioneer of computer art, passed away on July 16, 2022 at the age of 95. CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE is an homage to Franke’s MONDRIAN software developed for the Texas Instruments TI 99/4 home computer in 1979, and it’s a fundraiser to digitize his archive:

“Our goal is to raise 20,000 Euro so that ZKM Karlsruhe can digitize Herbert W. Franke’s 1,800 manuscripts and make them publicly available. If we raise more money, it will be donated to the Rütgers Foundation which supports children and young adults in Africa so that they can get access to and work with technology.” 

Each frame, a single “pixel” is added to the CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE image. When the software first loads, 100,000 frames are run in the background to start things off. Keep it running for hours or days to see it transform entirely — it’s an “infinite animation.”
